			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Federal prisons are heavily industrialized.  Check out <a href="http://www.unicor.gov/index.cfm" target="_blank" class="postlink">UNICOR</a>.
<br />

<br />
Most states have similar programs.  In New Jersey, you can frequently see prisoners collecting trash and performing landscaping duties along highways.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, the level where the least productive use of prisoner's time is made is at the local/county jail (housing prisoners typically for &lt; 1 year sentences for minor crimes- least that's how it goes in my state).  Of course, in many places these types of prisoners are eligible for work-release.
<br />

<br />
What isn't widely known, is that some states farm out prison labor to private companies.  This is pretty much slave labor (not subject to state/federal minimum wage requirements), as your option as a prisoner is to rot in your cell.  Working for $2 / hour  &gt; no work when you've been sentenced to years behind bars.
<br />

<br />
One of the things that was popular a few years ago, was using inmates for telemarketing labor.  Call up to order something from a catalog and you could be giving your credit card number to someone behind bars.  Also, I believe one major airline at one time used prison labor for their reservation assistance line.  Once word got out about this, a lot of companies, fearing consumer backlash, stopped using prison labor for these things.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
