			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Before the penitentiary reforms in the early-mid 19th century, prisons were cages in which people were locked in to die. The whole concept of <span style="font-style: italic">penitence</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">reform</span> instead of punishment was a Quaker concept. The federal prison system finally repudiated the concept of <span style="font-style: italic">reform</span> in 1970. Most states haven't formally repudiated it, but act as if it had been.
<br />

<br />
Jails are at the city/county level of authority and are for periods of incarceration of <span style="text-decoration: underline">no more than 1 year</span>. 
<br />
Prisons are at the state and federal level of authority and are where you get sent if your sentence is for more than 1 year.
<br />

<br />
The less-than/greater-than 1-year line is also the line between misdemeanors and felonies.
<br />

<br />
Ano, I don't think you have any clue at what sort of people are in prison. You ought to read Alexander Solzhenitsyn. Especially the one called Gulag Archipelago. 
<br />

<br />
I think y'all should take a look at the poorhouses of 17th and 18th century England. Read Charles Dickens if you can't find any real history books near where you live. The so-called bankruptcy reforms are taking us back to that era.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
